docs.abstract: “As athletes, we have a very unique opportunity to speak up about things that we believe in,” the American figure skater Adam Rippon said.
docs.snippet: “As athletes, we have a very unique opportunity to speak up about things that we believe in,” the American figure skater Adam Rippon said.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARK CITY, Utah — The protesting of racism and police brutality by American athletes started with W.N.B.A. players at a news conference in July 2016 and soon spread to the playing fields of the N.F.L. and the hardwood courts of the N.B.A. In less than five months, the Winter Games in Pyeongchang, South Korea, will present a far larger stage for demonstration: an Olympic podium.

headline.main: Might Athlete Protests Reach Podiums at the Winter Olympics?
headline.print_headline: How Far to Carry ‘Unique Opportunity to Speak Up’

docs.abstract: Being president has not changed Trump but exposed him.
docs.snippet: Being president has not changed Trump but exposed him.
docs.lead_paragraph: Allow me a moment of personal indulgence: When I began writing a column many years ago, it quickly dawned on me that although I had strong and firm views on some things, there were many others about which my opinions weren’t fully formed. I believe that many of us have areas in our lives where our opinions are fungible. It was only through my experience in this job that my own opinions became so clear to me. Doing the job honed me, revealed me, exposed me.

docs.abstract: Using firsthand accounts from teenagers to guide classroom discussions around race and racism.
docs.snippet: Using firsthand accounts from teenagers to guide classroom discussions around race and racism.
docs.lead_paragraph: This is a guest lesson from Jinnie Spiegler, the director of curriculum at the Anti-Defamation League. She has written for us previously on 10 Ways to Talk to Students About Sensitive Issues in the News.

headline.main: First Encounters With Race and Racism: Teaching Ideas for Classroom Conversations

docs.abstract: Celeste Ng’s “Little Fires Everywhere” witnesses the mysteries of arson, kinship and community in late-’90s suburban America.
docs.snippet: Celeste Ng’s “Little Fires Everywhere” witnesses the mysteries of arson, kinship and community in late-’90s suburban America.
docs.lead_paragraph: Readers of Celeste Ng’s second novel, “Little Fires Everywhere,” will recognize a few elements from her acclaimed debut, “Everything I Never Told You.” There are the simmering racial tensions and incendiary family dynamics beneath the surface of a quiet Ohio town. There are the appeal and impossibility of assimilation, the all-consuming force of motherhood and the secret lives of teenagers and their parents, each unknowable to the other.

headline.main: In a Quiet Ohio Town, Who Started the Fire, and Why?

docs.abstract: Amid protests against police brutality and in the wake of the president’s tweets, the war over television ratings has become explicitly political.
docs.snippet: Amid protests against police brutality and in the wake of the president’s tweets, the war over television ratings has become explicitly political.
docs.lead_paragraph: Nielsen’s television ratings are traditionally an industry metric, used by networks and advertisers to buy and sell commercial time. But on this Monday, and every Monday for the next four months, the N.F.L. ratings will be dissected far and wide in search of broader meaning.

headline.main: Reading Something in the N.F.L. Ratings? You’re Probably Wrong
headline.print_headline: Reading Something Into the N.F.L. Ratings? You’re Probably Wrong

docs.abstract: The wave of demonstrations at N.F.L. games on Sunday even included some of Trump’s supporters in the league, but it drew a mixed reception from fans.
docs.snippet: The wave of demonstrations at N.F.L. games on Sunday even included some of Trump’s supporters in the league, but it drew a mixed reception from fans.
docs.lead_paragraph: On three N.F.L. teams, nearly all the football players skipped the national anthem altogether. Dozens of others, from London to Los Angeles, knelt or locked arms on the sidelines, joined by several team owners in a league normally friendly to President Trump. Some of the sport’s biggest stars joined the kind of demonstration they have steadfastly avoided.

headline.main: Fueled by Trump’s Tweets, Anthem Protests Grow to a Nationwide Rebuke
headline.print_headline: Protesters Refuse to Stand on the Sidelines

docs.abstract: As parents of biracial kids, we shudder to say the word. But we have to.
docs.snippet: As parents of biracial kids, we shudder to say the word. But we have to.
docs.lead_paragraph: In recent days, we have read gut-wrenching accounts of an alleged attack on an 8-year-old biracial boy in Claremont, New Hampshire. Like the local police, who did not issue any public statements until more than a week after the incident, under pressure from the boy’s family, state media have also been circumspect in their coverage. Nowhere in the reporting by top state media outlets on this tragic event does the word “lynching” occur.

headline.main: Call a Lynching By Its Name

byline.original: By Sindiso Mnisi Weeks and Dan Weeks

docs.abstract: Across the country, players, coaches and owners staged protests during performances of the national anthem, reacting to comments from President Trump.
docs.snippet: Across the country, players, coaches and owners staged protests during performances of the national anthem, reacting to comments from President Trump.
docs.lead_paragraph: Widespread calls for demonstrations at Sunday's games erupted after President Trump's comments this weekend criticizing players for kneeling during the national anthem and owners for tolerating the displays. Starting with Jacksonville’s game against Baltimore in London, players, coaches and several owners protested across the league.

headline.main: What Every N.F.L. Team Did During the National Anthem on Sunday

byline.original: By Benjamin Hoffman and Lance Booth

docs.abstract: White House officials said President Trump is deeply worried that his recent show of bipartisanship endangers his standing with conservatives.
docs.snippet: White House officials said President Trump is deeply worried that his recent show of bipartisanship endangers his standing with conservatives.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump was restless on the flight home from his rally on Friday night in Alabama, griping about the size of the crowd, wondering how his pink tie played with his audience and fretting about the low energy of the Senate candidate he was there to bolster.

headline.main: Trump’s N.F.L. Critique a Calculated Attempt to Shore Up His Base
headline.print_headline: With N.F.L. Critique, Trump Makes Calculated Attempt to Shore Up Base

byline.original: By Glenn Thrush and Maggie Haberman

docs.abstract: In college, Kaepernick began a journey that led him to his position as one of the most prominent, if divisive, social activists in sports.
docs.snippet: In college, Kaepernick began a journey that led him to his position as one of the most prominent, if divisive, social activists in sports.
docs.lead_paragraph: The standout college quarterback went to the meeting alone that winter night, looking to join. The fraternity brothers at Kappa Alpha Psi, a predominantly black fraternity with a small chapter at the University of Nevada, knew who he was. He was a tall, lean, biracial junior, less than a year from graduating with a business degree.
